{{Use Australian English|date=April 2018}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}
[[Image:ClipperRoute.png|thumb|right|250px|The clipper route followed by ships sailing between England and Australia/New Zealand.]]
In [[sailing]], the '''clipper route''' was the traditional route derived from the [[Brouwer Route]] and sailed by [[clipper|clipper ships]] between [[Europe]] and the [[Far East]], [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]].  The route ran from west to east through the [[Southern Ocean]], in order to make use of the strong westerly winds of the [[Roaring Forties]].  Many ships and sailors were lost in the heavy conditions along the route, particularly at [[Cape Horn]], which the clippers had to round on their return to Europe.

The clipper route fell into commercial disuse with the introduction of [[steamboat|steam ships]], and the opening of the [[Suez Canal|Suez]] and [[Panama Canal]]s.  However, it remains the fastest sailing route around the world, and as such has been the route for several prominent [[yacht racing|yacht races]], such as the ''[[Around Alone]]'' and ''[[Vendée Globe]]''.

== Australia and New Zealand ==
[[File:Unidentified tall ship near Cape Horn - Nla.pic-vn3299637-v.jpg|thumb|right|Unidentified ship rounding Cape Horn]] 
The clipper route from [[England]] to Australia and New Zealand, returning via [[Cape Horn]], offered captains the fastest [[circumnavigation]] of the world, and hence potentially the greatest rewards; many grain, wool and gold clippers sailed this route, returning home with valuable cargos in a relatively short time.  However, this route, passing south of the three [[great capes]] and running for much of its length through the [[Southern Ocean]], also carried the greatest risks, exposing ships to the hazards of fierce winds, huge waves, and [[iceberg]]s.  This combination of the fastest ships, the highest risks, and the greatest rewards combined to give this route a particular aura of romance and drama.<ref name=Chichester>{{cite book |title=Along the Clipper Way |first=Francis |last=Chichester |pages=15–16 |publisher=Hodder & Stoughton |year=1966 |isbn=0-340-00191-7}}</ref>

=== Outbound ===

This route ran from England down the east [[Atlantic Ocean]] to the [[Equator]], crossing at about the position of [[Saint Peter and Paul Rocks]], around [[20th meridian west|20 degrees west]].  A good sailing time for the {{convert|3275|mi|km}} to this point would have been around 21 days; however, an unlucky ship could spend an additional three weeks crossing the [[Intertropical Convergence Zone|doldrums]].<ref>''Along the Clipper Way''; pages 44–45.</ref>

The route then ran south through the western South Atlantic, following the natural circulation of winds and currents, passing close to [[Trindade and Martim Vaz|Trindade]], then curving south-east past [[Tristan da Cunha]].<ref>''Along the Clipper Way''; page 47.</ref><ref>''Along the Clipper Way''; page 54.</ref>  The route crossed the [[Prime Meridian|Greenwich meridian]] at about [[40th parallel south|40 degrees south]], taking the clippers into the [[Roaring Forties]] after about {{convert|6500|mi|km}} sailed from [[Plymouth]].  A good time for this run would have been about 43 days.<ref>''Along the Clipper Way''; pages 57–58.</ref>

Once into the forties, a ship was also inside the ice zone, the area of the Southern Ocean where there was a significant chance of encountering [[iceberg]]s.  Safety would dictate keeping to the north edge of this zone, roughly along the parallel of [[40th parallel south|40 degrees south]]; however, the [[great circle]] route from the [[Cape of Good Hope]] to Australia, curving down to [[60th parallel south|60 degrees south]], is {{convert|1000|mi|km}} shorter, and would also offer the strongest winds.  Ship's masters would therefore go as far south as they dared, weighing the risk of ice against a fast passage.<ref>''Along the Clipper Way''; pages 74–75.</ref>

The clipper ships bound for Australia and New Zealand would call at a variety of ports.  A ship sailing from Plymouth to [[Sydney]], for example, would cover around {{convert|13750|mi|km}}; a fast time for this passage would be around 100 days.<ref>''Along the Clipper Way''; page 7.</ref>  ''[[Cutty Sark]]'' made the fastest passage on this route by a clipper, in 72 days.<ref>''Along the Clipper Way''; page 8.</ref>  ''[[Thermopylae (clipper)|Thermopylae]]'' made the slightly shorter passage from London to [[Melbourne]], {{convert|13150|mi|km}}, in just 61 days in 1868–69.<ref name="Along the Clipper Way; page 68">''Along the Clipper Way''; page 68.</ref>

The following map traces the outbound route of the 1874 voyage from [[London]] to [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]], of the clipper ship ''[[City of Adelaide (1864)|City of Adelaide]]'', which today is the world's oldest surviving clipper ship. The latitudes and longitudes are obtained from the surviving diary of 21-year-old passenger James McLauchlan.<ref name=JMdiary>{{cite web |url=http://cityofadelaide.org/wiki/Diary_of_James_McLauchlan |title=Diary of James Anderson McLauchlan |work=City of Adelaide – the Splendid Clipper Ship|publisher= CSCOAL|accessdate=3 April 2012}}</ref>

